INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3000','letter','1775-07-15','Saratoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I wish I may be able to proceed to Ticonderoga, as I am very much wanted there, the greatest confusion having taken place in the controversy between the officers claiming the command in that quarter.','ltr_pjs3000.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3001','letter','1775-07-18','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','You will expect that I should say something about this place and the troops here. Not one earthly thing for offence or defence has been done ; the commanding officer has no orders','ltr_pjs3001.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3002','letter','1775-07-31','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Since my last I have been most assiduously employed in preparing materials for building boats to convey me across the Lake. ','ltr_pjs3002.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3003','letter','1775-08-06','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Immediately on my arrival here, I issued such orders respecting the provisions and stores, (which I found had been most scandalously embezzled or misapplied,) as I hoped would effectually have brought matters into a right train','ltr_pjs3003.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3004','letter','1775-08-27','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','on my arrival at Saratoga, I received information, that a large body of Indians of the Six Nations were to be here on Tuesday last, and that my presence was indispensably necessary.','ltr_pjs3004.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3005','letter','1775-08-31','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','General Montgomery leaves Crown Point to-day, with twelve hundred men and four twelve-pounders. I follow him this evening','ltr_pjs3005.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3006','letter','1775-09-20','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','We approached half a mile nearer and then landed without opposition, in a close, deep swamp, which extended to very near the fort. Here we formed, and marched in the best order we could towards the fort, to reconnoitre.','ltr_pjs3006.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3007','letter','1775-09-26','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','If Job had been a General in my situation, his memory had not been so famous for patience. But the glorious end we have in view, and which I have confident hope will be attained, will atone for all.','ltr_pjs3007.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3008','letter','1775-10-12','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am extremely apprehensive that a want of powder will be fatal to our operations. I have sent Express to Albany and New York, but have not yet learnt whether I shall be supplied or not.','ltr_pjs3008.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3009','letter','1775-10-26','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','The reduction of Chamblee will, in all probability, be followed by that of St. John\'s, especially as General Montgomery has now a supply of powder','ltr_pjs3009.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3010','letter','1775-11-06','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Should success crown our endeavours at St. John\'s, of which there seems to be little doubt, the entire reduction of Canada will, in all probability, be the consequence','ltr_pjs3010.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3011','letter','1775-11-28','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','The evening before General Montgomery landed on the Island of Montreal, Mr. Carleton embarked his garrison on board of some vessels and small craft, and made two attempts to pass our batteries','ltr_pjs3011.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3012','letter','1776-01-05','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','now or never is the time for every virtuous American to exert himself in the cause of liberty and his country ; and that it is become a duty cheer fully to sacrifice the sweets of domestic felicity, to attain the honest, and glorious end America has in view','ltr_pjs3012.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3013','letter','1776-01-13','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','My amiable friend, the gallant Montgomery, is no more ; the brave Arnold is wounded; and we have met with a severe check in an unsuccessful attempt on Quebec.','ltr_pjs3013.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3014','letter','1776-04-12','Fort George','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','All is in readiness to move, as soon as the Lakes open, which, I hope, will be in a day or two.','ltr_pjs3014.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3015','letter','1776-06-12','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have, within this half hour, received a letter from General Arnold, of which the inclosed is a copy. I fear the next will announce the evacuation of Canada by our troops, probably with loss','ltr_pjs3015.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3016','letter','1776-04-25','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','The grief I feel on the evacuation of Canada by our troops, is greatly alleviated by the little loss sustained in the retreat, and the hope I have, that we shall maintain a superiority on the Lakes.','ltr_pjs3016.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3017','letter','1776-07-01','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Yesterday morning General Gates introduced a Mr. Avery to me, who applied to me for money to carry on the Commissary-General\'s department here. I asked if Mr. Livingston was superseded, and begged to see how he (Avery) was authorized to act here.','ltr_pjs3017.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3018','letter','1776-09-09','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am informed that the army is in the greatest distress for medicines. As every misfortune and want they labor under is imputed to me, so is this.','ltr_pjs3018.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3019','letter','1777-06-14','Saratoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Our numbers are so few to the northward, and we have so little prospect of their increasing, that should a disaster befall us at Ticonderoga, we should have very few troops indeed to oppose them.','ltr_pjs3019.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3020','letter','1777-06-16','Fort Edward','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','If the information which Amsbury gives is to be relied upon, as I think it is, we shall soon be air tacked at Ticonderoga','ltr_pjs3020.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3021','letter','1777-06-28','Albany','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Should an accident happen to the garrison of Ticonderoga, and General Burgoyne make a push to gain the south part of the Lake, I know of no obstacle to prevent him.','ltr_pjs3021.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3022','letter','1777-07-07','Saratoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','just before they arrived at Skenesborough, they were overtaken by the enemy\'s vessels and gunboats, and were obliged to abandon the vessels, in which we lost all our ammunition.','ltr_pjs3022.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3023','letter','1777-07-09','Fort Edward','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','Since I wrote you from Saratoga, I have not been able to learn what is become of General St. Clair and the enemy. The army followed the troops that came to Skenesborough as far as Fort Ann, where they were yesterday repulsed ','ltr_pjs3023.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3024','letter','1777-07-14','Fort Edward','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','On the 12th instant General St. Clair arrived here. As he fell in with Hudson\'s River about twelve miles below this, I ordered the troops to halt at Fort Miller, having no kind of shelter for them at any other place','ltr_pjs3024.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3025','letter','1777-07-28','Saratoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','So far from the militia that are with me increasing , they are daily diminishing, and I am very confident that in ten days, if the enemy should not Disturb us, we shall not have five hundred left','ltr_pjs3025.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3026','letter','1777-08-04','Stillwater','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','By the unanimous advice of all the General Officers, I have moved the army to this place. We propose to fortify our camp, in hopes that re-enforcements will enable us to keep our ground','ltr_pjs3026.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3027','letter','1777-08-19','Van Schaicks Island','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have the honor to congratulate your Excellency on a signal victory gained by General Stark over a detachment of about fifteen hundred of the enemy near Bennington','ltr_pjs3027.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3200','letter','1780-03-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I do not mean, Sir, to convey the most distant idea, that I solicit a restoration to the rank and place I held in the army','ltr_pjs3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3201','letter','1780-03-07','Philadelphia','PA','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I believe it will be necessary for General Greene to address Congress very pointedly on the subject of the wagoners, as I find a disposition in many to have them drawn from the army.','ltr_pjs3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3202','letter','1780-04-05','Philadelphia','PA','US','Philip','Schuyler','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have entreated General Greene to remain a day or two longer in town, that I may be able to advise with him on the measures necessary to be pursued to prevent the ill consequences of his being driven to the necessity of a resignation','ltr_pjs3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('pjs3203','letter','1777-07-31','Saratoga','NY','US','Philip','Schuyler','','Benjamin','Lincoln','','individual','','As General Burgoyne is advancing towards us, and as a movement of a body of troops from the Grants towards Skenesborough will doubtless much embarrass him','ltr_pjs3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
